article.description:
Allison Feaster scored 20 points as the Charlotte Sting beat Washington 67-57 on Tuesday night to gain homecourt advantage in their first-round playoff series against the
Mystics.
article.headline: Sting earn first-round home-court edge over Mystics
article.linkText: Sting gain early home-court edge by beating Mystics
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Allison Feaster scored 20 points as the
Charlotte Sting beat Washington 67-57 on Tuesday night to gain
homecourt advantage in their first-round playoff series against the
Mystics.

	   Tammy Sutton-Brown added 17 points and seven rebounds as the
Sting (18-14) won their fourth straight game to take the second
seed in the Eastern Conference playoffs.

	   The best-of-three playoff series will begin in Washington on
Thursday night, and shift to Charlotte for Game 2 on Saturday, and
Game 3, if necessary, on Monday.

	   "We wanted to get homecourt advantage, but we also wanted to
set the tone,'' Sting coach Anne Donovan said. "We wanted to make
sure we went into the playoffs playing our best. I feel so pleased
with how we finished and I think we're coming together right now.''

	   Vicky Bullett had 11 points, and Annie Burgess and Helen Luz
added 10 each for the Mystics (17-15), who led the conference most
of the season before dropping nine of their last 11 games to finish
third. Washington star Chamique Holdsclaw had eight points on
4-of-17 shooting.

	   "I missed a couple of chippies and I really didn't have my
balance,'' Holdsclaw said. "They did a good job getting under me,
but I think next time I'll come out more focused.''

	   Andrea Stinson's 3-pointer capped a 10-3 run early in the second
half that gave the Sting a 44-31 lead. Sutton-Brown's 3-point play
with 3:12 left made it 63-53 and ended Washington's chances.

	   The Sting were 6-of-18 from 3-point range, including a 4-of-8
performance from Feaster, to finish the season with a WNBA-record
211 3-pointers.

	   "I really have no explanation for it, but it has certainly
become one of our biggest weapons,'' said Feaster, who hit 79
3-pointers. "My teammates really do a good job to create shots and
we've been able to knock those 3s down.''

	   Charlotte shot just 35 percent, but made 19 of 20 free throws
and had a 30-27 rebounding edge.

	   "We can't afford to put them on the line 20 times,'' Mystics
coach Marianne Stanley said. "This game doesn't affect the fact
that we have a best-of-three series to play now. We can fix the
things that hurt us.''
